data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users meet a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*
- **`Assert.IsTrue` with messages** — always add a message string when using `IsTrue` for conditions
- **`CollectionAssert`** — use for richer collection checks:

```csharp
// No nulls in the list
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// All items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Check exact contents (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, users);

// Check same items regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, users);

// Check an item is present
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer the most specific assertion — it gives the best diagnostics on failure.
